article.description: Amber Obaze hit a 35-footer with 1.2 seconds left to give No. 12 Louisiana Tech an 87-84 victory over No. 6 Penn State on Sunday.
article.headline: La Tech buzzer beater downs Lady Lions
article.linkText: La Tech ends No. 6 Penn State's home win streak
article.story:
STATE COLLEGE, Pa. (AP) -- Louisiana Tech's Amber Obaze was as
surprised as anyone when she tossed up a game-winning 35-footer.

Obaze's bank shot from beyond the arc with 1.2 seconds left gave
No. 12 Louisiana Tech an 87-84 victory over No. 6 Penn State on
Sunday, ending the Lady Lions' 24-game home winning streak.

"That was a prayer -- that was a total prayer," Obaze said.
"It was either going to be my day or somebody else's. I looked up
and I didn't see anything else to do except shoot it."

That's not what Obaze usually does. It was her only 3-point
attempt of the game, and just her eighth of the season for the Lady
Techsters (7-1).

"Actually, Amber hesitated right away and scared me to death,"
coach Kurt Budke said. "It was a lucky shot. You've got to get
lucky once in a while."

That's also why, despite the clock, Penn State (7-2) wasn't
looking for Obaze to shoot.

Jess Strom's 3-pointer with 8 seconds left tied the game at
82-all, but Obaze took the inbounds pass and dribbled to about 8
feet from the right hash mark before putting up a desperation
jumper that gave Tech the lead.

"We should have been guarding her closer," Kelly Mazzante
said. "I obviously thought she was going to penetrate, but with
the score like that somebody should have been on her."

And that's when things really got tense.

Although the clock showed 0.1 seconds to play, Tech's players
stormed the court in celebration, thinking the game was over.

Budke quickly got his players back on the bench, but Penn State
coach Rene Portland -- who spent most of the game in a wheelchair
after breaking her left leg when she slipped on ice Thursday --
hobbled onto the court on crutches to argue that the Lady Techsters
should be called for a technical foul.

That would have given Penn State a free throw and the ball at
halfcourt instead of under Tech's basket.

"The shot was made, and they went out on the floor and
celebrated," Portland said. "None of them could give me an
explanation that was viable other than, 'Let's get going, let's get
going."

No technical was called, and the clock was reset with 1.2
seconds left.

Erica Smith-Taylor fouled Tanisha Wright on the inbounds pass,
sending the Lady Lions to the free throw line with 1.1 seconds
left. Wright made the first free throw, then missed the second,
putting the rebound in play and giving the Lady Lions a chance to
tie with a tip-in.

But a lane violation on the second free throw forced Wright to
shoot again. This time, Wright banked it in, leaving Penn State
down 85-84 and giving the ball back to Tech.

"Believe me, I didn't mean to make it," Wright said. "I tried
to do the same exact thing I did the first time, but I guess it was
maybe an inch too far to the right."

Mazzante was called for an intentional foul on the inbounds, and
Tasha Crain hit both free throws to make it 87-84. Tech then
inbounded the ball and ran out the clock.

Amisha Carter had 17 points and 13 rebounds for the Lady
Techsters, and Erica Smith-Carter also scored 17 points. Obaze,
Crain and Trina Frierson each had 14.

Mazzante scored 29 points, Wright had 19 and Strom 16 for the
Lady Lions.

Wright scored the first five points in an 11-0 Penn State run
that gave the Lady Lions a 48-43 lead about four minutes into the
second half.

But the Lady Techsters inched their way back, taking a 60-59
lead on Tiffany Thompson's inside jumper. Neither team led by more
than five points in the second half.

"That was the ball game right there," Budke said. "I was
really disappointed in my club the first four minutes of the second
half. ... To be able to battle out of that, and come out of that
and start scoring again and get yourself back in the ball game,
says a lot about our team."

Louisiana Tech's speed and pressure defense flustered Penn State
in the first half. The Lady Techsters held Penn State without a
field goal for almost five minutes midway through the half,
allowing Tech to take a 29-20 lead on two free throws by Carter.

Tech led 41-35 at halftime.
